solution:
First, we combine like terms in the expression: \begin{align*}
(15x^3+80x-5)&-(-4x^3+4x-5)\\
&=15x^3+80x-5+4x^3-4x+5\\
&=19x^3+76x.\end{align*}We can factor out a $19x$ from the expression, to get $$19x^3+76x=\boxed{19x(x^2+4)}.$$
model_solution:
Step 1: Combine like terms:
\[(15x^3+80x-5)-(-4x^3+4x-5) = 15x^3+80x-5+4x^3-4x+5 = 19x^3+76x.\]
Factor out the greatest common factor (GCF) from the terms.

19x^3+76x=19x(x^2+4)
Factor the difference of squares in the expression x^2+4.

19x(x^2+4)=19x((x+2i)(x-2i))
Factor the expression (x+2i)(x-2i).

19x((x+2i)(x-2i))=19x(x^2-4i^2)=19x(x^2+4)
19x(x^2+4)=19x(x^2+2^2)
Factor the difference of squares in the expression x^2+4^2.

19x(x^2+4^2)=19x((x+2i)(x-2i))
19x((x+2i)(x-2i))=19x(x^2+4)
Factor the difference of squares in the expression x^2+4.
19x(x^2+2^2) = 19x(x+2i)(x-2i)
19x(x^2+2^2) = 19x(x+2i)(x-2i)
